Ever notice your Spark job suddenly splits into exactly 200 tasks — no matter how much data you have? That number isn't magic, and understanding it is the start of tuning Spark.

Start with the partition. A partition is Spark's unit of parallelism: one partition becomes one task, and one task runs on one core. That mapping is the whole game.

If you have more partitions than cores, that's fine — tasks queue up and your cores stay busy. But if you have fewer partitions than cores, some cores just sit idle, and you're leaving speed on the table.

So where does 200 come from? After any shuffle — a groupBy, a join — Spark sets the number of output partitions from a config called spark dot sql dot shuffle dot partitions, and it defaults to 200. On a tiny dataset that's 200 nearly-empty tasks; on a huge one it might be far too few. It's a default, not an answer.

Right-sizing partitions to your data and your cores is one of the biggest levers in Spark performance.

Partitions are Module 3 — link's in the description.
